{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e5c33e64-49c6-4d0e-8685-e2c4a9d53959","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws` (xUnit/NUnit) instead — it's more precise and doesn't risk passing if the wrong line throws:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\n**Why?**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call\n- You can also capture the exception to assert on its message:\n\n```csharp\nvar ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n    () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\nAssert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"11d3190f-75a9-43bb-9096-0533e594dde7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question - no need to explore the codebase.","outputTokens":279,"requestId":"D000:91905:1538487:1896CFE:69EC165E"},"id":"9f48467a-4b4b-4417-a6b2-e0abfebb6de3","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:18:28.523Z","parentId":"036c3497-7d73-4eda-82cb-7cb395a88f08"}
